{"key":"post-12939773","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12939773</id>\n<content>Actually, what you want to use is field aged manure.&amp;nbsp; This is horse or cow manure that's been sitting out in the sun and rain for a few months.&amp;nbsp; It will smell like grass and break up easily without getting your hands dirty.&amp;nbsp; It's not just about drying, it's about aging.&amp;nbsp; You want all the ammonia smell to be gone from the manure before use.&amp;nbsp; If it were me, I'd go back to the stables and collect manure from the field, rather than the barns or what they sweep/shovel out of the stalls.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If other mushrooms are fruiting in the manure, I'd spread it around your flowerbeds as fertilizer and get some more for mushroom growing.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>12939624</prev>\n<first>12939559</first>\n<last>12939773</last>\n<when>1279896469</when>\n<utime>07/23/10 05:47 PM</utime>\n</post>"}